5000|$|At the {{molecular}} level, endonuclease <b>gene</b> <b>drives</b> {{work by cutting}} chromosomes that do not encode the drive at a specific site, inducing the cell {{to repair the damage}} by copying the drive sequence onto the damaged chromosome. This is derived from genome editing techniques and similarly relies on the fact that double strand breaks are most frequently repaired by homologous recombination if a template is present, and less often by non-homologous end joining. The cell then has two copies of the drive sequence. To achieve this behavior, endonuclease <b>gene</b> <b>drives</b> consist of two nested elements: ...|$|R
